ile those that fall short are less likely to be tried later. Based on this idea of adaptation, the authors construct formal models of party competition, turnout, and voters' choices of candidates. These models predict substantial turnout levels, voters sorting into parties, and winning parties adopting centrist platforms. In multiparty elections, voters are able to coordinate vote choices on majority-preferred candidates, while all candidates garner significant vote shares. Overall, the behavioral theory and its models produce macroimplications consistent with the data on elections, and they use plausible microassumptions about the cognitive capacities of politicians and voters. A computational model accompanies the book and can be used as a tool for further research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBehaviorism (Political science). 0aVotingxPsychological aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  aCondorcet winner.  aDownsian party competition.  aDuverger's Law.  aMarkov chain.  aPareto dominance.  aadaptation.  aaspiration-based adaptation.  aaspiration-based adaptive rule.  aaspiration-based adjustment.  aaspirations.  abandwagon effect.  abehavior.  abehavioral theory.  abounded rationality.  acandidates.  acomputational model.  adecision making.  aelection voting.  aelections.  aequilibrium behavior.  afaction size.  aframing.  agame-theoretic model.  ahedonics.  aheuristics.  aincumbent.  amajority faction.  amultiparty elections.  aparties.  aparty affiliation.  aparty competition.  apayoffs.  aplatforms.  apolitical parties.  apoliticians.  apopulation size.  apropensity.  arational choice theory.  arational choice.  arationality.  aretrospective voting.  asatisficing.  asearch behav